<article>
    <h1>Les&#xAD;son learnt in safety</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200827/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-08-27"><time>2020-08-27</time></a>
        - <span>BIG PICTURE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Ortho­dox Jewish yeshiva (reli­gious school) students study­ing sep­a­rated by plas­tic cells set up amid the coro­n­avirus pan­demic, on Tues­day, in the south­ern Is­raeli city of Sderot.</p>
    <p>Con­fi­dent it had beaten Covid-19 and des­per­ate to re­boot the econ­omy, the Is­raeli gov­ern­ment had re­opened schools in late May.</p>
    <p>Within days, how­ever, in­fec­tions were re­ported at a Jerusalem high school, which quickly mush­roomed into the largest out­break in a sin­gle school in Is­rael.</p>
    <p>The les­son, ex­perts told The New York Times, is that even com­mu­ni­ties that have got the spread of the virus un­der con­trol need to take strict pre­cau­tions when re­open­ing schools.</p>
    <p>Smaller classes, mask wear­ing, keep­ing desks six feet apart and pro­vid­ing ad­e­quate ven­ti­la­tion, they say, are likely to be cru­cial un­til a vac­cine is avail­able.</p>
    <p>On Mon­day, Is­rael’s Ed­u­ca­tion Min­is­ter Yoav Galant, Health Min­is­ter Yuli Edel­stein, and Covid-19 project man­ager Ronni Gamzu agreed that the school year would open as planned on Sept 1, un­der re­stric­tions, Xin­hua re­ported.</p>
    <p>How­ever, it is pos­si­ble that the open­ing of high schools in cities with high mor­bid­ity will be post­poned, ac­cord­ing to a state­ment is­sued by the Health Min­istry.</p>

